<DOC><DOCNO> AP880627-0094 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1228EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Botswana     06-27 0251</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Botswana,0258</SECOND><HEAD>Another South African Arrested In Connection With Raid</HEAD><DATELINE>GABORONE, Botswana (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A third South African has beenarrested in connection with an army incursion into Botswana,authorities said Monday.   Barry Viviers appeared in magistrate's court on a charge ofunlawful possession of a hand grenade found at his home Friday.   Police said Viviers, who lives in Gaborone, had been in contactwith a suspected South African commando, Theodore Hermansen, on theday before the June 20 cross-border mission.   During the incursion, a five-member South African army unitfired at a group of Botswana policemen, injuring three officers.Those five soldiers escaped back to South Africa, but Hermansen anda colleague, Johannes Basson, were arrested at a roadblock and havebeen charged with violating Botswana's National Security Act.   Viviers, 20, was ordered held pending a bail application laterthis week. He was born in Botswana but lived for most of his lifein South Africa before returning to Gaborone a few years ago.   South African officials have said the army unit entered Botswanaon an intelligence mission as part of the campaign to combat theAfrican National Congress guerrilla movement. It has neitherconfirmed nor denied Botswana's allegation that Hermansen andBasson were linked to the mission.   Botswana said the commandos planned a raid on a target inGaborone and has accused South Africa of ``state terrorism.''   South Africa claims its soldiers fired at the policemen afterbeing fired at first. Botswama says the police patrol was unarmed.</TEXT></DOC>